# Codex Subagent Workflow

## Purpose

This project already defines a Cursor-oriented multi-agent split under `.cursor/agents/`.
This document adds the matching Codex dispatch contract so the same role model can be reused with Codex subagents.

## Source Of Truth

- Shared project briefing: `AGENTS.md`
- Cursor role files: `.cursor/agents/`
- Codex role files: `.codex/agents/`

Cursor and Codex should keep the same role boundaries unless there is a documented reason to diverge.

## Current Codex Behavior

In the current Codex runtime used for this project, subagents are not spawned automatically from `.codex/agents/` files or from role names alone.

What actually happens:

1. The main Codex agent decides whether to call `spawn_agent`.
2. If it does, the main agent must pass the relevant role instructions in the dispatch message.
3. Without that explicit dispatch step, `.codex/agents/` remains reference material only.
4. In the current Codex runtime for this session, the main agent should only use `spawn_agent` when the user explicitly asks for subagents, delegation, or parallel agent work.

Operationally, this means the project can define backend, frontend, QA, and security roles, but Codex will only use them when the main agent deliberately delegates work.

For this Codex environment, the current runtime policy is stricter than Cursor-style automatic role loading:

- role files do not auto-activate
- subagents are not created just because a matching file exists
- delegation requires an explicit `spawn_agent` call by the main agent

## Role Mapping

| Responsibility | Cursor file | Codex file | Recommended Codex agent type |
|---|---|---|---|
| Backend implementation | `.cursor/agents/backend-worker.md` | `.codex/agents/backend-worker.md` | `worker` |
| Frontend implementation | `.cursor/agents/frontend-worker.md` | `.codex/agents/frontend-worker.md` | `worker` |
| QA verification | `.cursor/agents/qa-verifier.md` | `.codex/agents/qa-verifier.md` | `worker` |
| Security review | `.cursor/agents/security-reviewer.md` | `.codex/agents/security-reviewer.md` | `explorer` by default |

## Dispatch Contract

1. The main Codex agent reads `AGENTS.md` and the matching file under `.codex/agents/`.
2. The dispatch message must assign explicit ownership, such as `src/` or `public/`.
3. Parallel frontend/backend dispatch is allowed only when write scopes are disjoint.
4. Every dispatched worker must be told that it is not alone in the codebase and must not revert edits it did not make.
5. The verifier runs after implementation. The security reviewer is used for sensitive changes or provider-related work.
